  Specifically, distilly vendors and adapts the local HTML-to-markdown engine
  from curl.md's `src/md/`. The carve-out kept:

    - `fromHtml` — the pure unified/rehype/remark HTML-to-markdown conversion
      (`src/md/fromHtml.ts`).
    - the pure per-site Profiles registry and its generator-keyed detection
      (`src/md/profiles.ts` + the pure `detectPageProfile`/`defineProfile`
      parts of `src/md/mod.ts`), as a starter subset.
    - the network URL-rewriter Rules and the pure rule match/dispatch
      (`src/md/rules.ts`, `src/md/rules/*` + the pure orchestration parts of
      `src/md/mod.ts`), as a starter subset, confined behind the
      `distilly/fetch` entrypoint.

  The carve-out removed (left in curl.md's server, not vendored):

    - curl.md's hosted-service client and its npm client.
    - the network `mod.ts` fetch wrapper, including its default of
      `globalThis.fetch`; distilly bakes in NO `fetch` and reaches the network
      only through a caller-injected `fetch` seam (see
      `docs/adr/0001-rule-vs-profile-and-injected-fetch.md`).
    - the type-only `#db` import and the `hono`/Cloudflare/transport coupling.
    - `tokenx` source-token accounting and the `zod`-backed heavier rule paths
      (authenticated GitHub GraphQL/REST, MDN browser-compat fetches).

  Truncation to the size presets is distilly's own code (`src/truncate.ts`),
  not curl.md's `chunk`. The vendored portions remain under the MIT License
  above.

  distilly does NOT use curl.md's hosted service or its npm client; it performs
  conversion locally and reaches the network only through the caller-injected
  `fetch`.
